<TITLE> Shooter of Alabama Gov Wallace freed after 35 years </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Sat Nov 10, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The man who shot and paralyzed Alabama Gov. George Wallace during the 1972 US presidential race was released from prison on Friday, prison officials said. Arthur Bremer, who shot Wallace and three others as the governor campaigned in Maryland for the Democratic presidential nomination, wrote in his diary that he acted to gain fame. Bremer served 35 years but was released 17 years early from a Maryland prison because of good behavior. Prison officials gave no further details, saying they were shielding his privacy to help him readjust to today's world. Bremer, who was convicted of attempted murder, must stay in Maryland and be monitored. Wallace, known for his racist policies and statements, was a four-time Alabama governor and ran unsuccessfully for US president four times. He later became a born-again Christian and repudiated his racist views. After the shooting he was in a wheelchair until his death in 19
